public Object getSafeValue(JSONObject item, String key, ItemType tp)
{
    if ((item == null) || (!item.has(key))) {
        return null; //The object was null or is missing the key
    }
    switch (tp) {
        case ItemType.STRING: return item.getString(key);
        case ItemType.BOOLEAN: return item.getBoolean(key);
        case ItemType.INT: return item.getInt(key);
        case ItemType.FLOAT: return item.getFloat(key);
        case ItemType.JSONOBJECT: return item.getJSONObject;
        default: return null;
    }
}
```

Here, we have exactly one `if`: it&#39;s checking whether `item` exists and has the `key` we are searching for. From here on, you can call `getSafeValue` like this:

```
id = getSafeValue(book, &quot;id&quot;, ItemType.STRING);
```

or this:

```
listPriceAmmount = getSafeValue(listPrice, &quot;amount&quot;, ItemType.FLOAT);
```

Of course, `ItemType` is an `enum` with the purpose of guaranteeing ease of use.

